Content:
Yes — and this is actually the **cleanest possible answer** to your question. Here's the direct analysis:

---

## Yes, absolutely — and `embed2` already *does* import only those four packages

Look at `rye.go`:

```go
import (
    "github.com/refaktor/rye/env"
    "github.com/refaktor/rye/evaldo"
    "github.com/refaktor/rye/loader"
)
```

(`base` is pulled in transitively via `evaldo.RegisterBaseBuiltins`.) That's exactly the minimal set you're thinking of.

**The problem is NOT what `embed2` imports — it's that `go.mod` is still a single flat module pointing at `../` (the whole rye repo via `replace`), and Go resolves the full transitive closure of that module's dependencies at module level, regardless of which packages are actually compiled.**

---

## Why selective package imports don't save you here

Go's module system works in two layers:

| Layer | What it does |
|---|---|
| **Module** (`go.mod`) | Lists *all* deps the module *could* need, resolved at download/tidy time |
| **Package** (import graph) | Determines what actually *compiles* into your binary |

When you do `replace github.com/refaktor/rye => ../`, you're pulling in the entire rye module. `go mod tidy` walks **every** `.go` file in every package of that module (subject to build tags) and unions all their `require` statements into `embed2/go.mod`. That's why `fsnotify`, `govector`, `yaml.v3`, `x/crypto` etc. all appear — not because `embed2` uses them, but because *some package somewhere in the rye module* does.

So even if `embed2/rye.go` only imports `env`, `loader`, `evaldo` — if `security/policy.go` (which no one calls) has `import "gopkg.in/yaml.v3"` with no build tag, `yaml.v3` ends up in `embed2/go.mod`.

---

## The two-part fix that makes your intuition actually work

**Part 1 — Build tags** (already mostly done in rye): The build tag approach (`no_baseio`, `no_vector`) *does* work at the **compile** layer — those packages won't be compiled in. But `go mod tidy` still adds the deps to `go.mod` unless every file that imports them is properly guarded. The two leaks are `util/securesave.go` and `security/policy.go` — no build tags, so `x/crypto` and `yaml.v3` always appear in `go.mod`.

**Part 2 — The module boundary**: The ultimate clean solution is what `embed2` structurally *wants* to be — **its own Go module** (separate `go.mod`, not a `replace` pointing at the monorepo). If `embed2` were a real standalone module that only `go get`s the specific packages it needs from a *published* rye release, its `go.mod` would only list what those packages' own import chains require. But as long as it uses `replace ../`, it inherits the entire rye module's dependency surface.

---

## Short answer

Your instinct is correct in spirit but Go's module system makes it insufficient on its own. Importing only `env/loader/evaldo/base` *does* limit what **compiles**, but `go.mod` still reflects the entire rye module's deps. You need **both**:
1. Proper build tags on every heavy file in rye (fix `securesave.go` + `policy.go`)
2. Either proper tag enforcement in `embed2`, OR making `embed2` a genuinely separate module from the main rye binary/REPL

The REPL, `main.go`, CLI flags etc. don't contribute to the problem directly — they're just the reason those heavy packages *exist* in the rye repo at all.
---

